content.text:
The issue was that `IndentationRule` incorrectly calculated the indentation of lambda parameters when the lambda was part of a multiline call expression but using a non-standard code style (not `ktlint_official`). Specifically, it tried to align the parameters with the function name + ` { `, assuming a single-line layout (e.g. `foo { param ->`), even when the call spanned multiple lines (e.g. `foo(\n...) { param ->`). This resulted in excessive or incorrect indentation.

The fix involves detecting if there is a newline between the start of the `CALL_EXPRESSION` and the start of the `FUNCTION_LITERAL`. If a newline is detected, we fall back to a standard indentation (double indent) instead of trying to align horizontally with the function call start.

I modified `ktlint-ruleset-standard/src/main/kotlin/com/pinterest/ktlint/ruleset/standard/rules/IndentationRule.kt` to add this check in the `calculateIndentOfFunctionLiteralParameters` extension function.

I verified the fix by creating a reproduction test case in `ktlint-ruleset-standard/src/test/kotlin/com/pinterest/ktlint/ruleset/standard/rules/IndentationRuleLambdaTest.kt`, confirming it failed before the fix and passed after the fix. I also ran existing tests in `IndentationRuleTest.kt` to ensure no regressions. I deleted the temporary test file before finishing.

```kotlin
// ktlint-ruleset-standard/src/main/kotlin/com/pinterest/ktlint/ruleset/standard/rules/IndentationRule.kt

// ... inside calculateIndentOfFunctionLiteralParameters ...
            parent(CALL_EXPRESSION)
                ?.let { callExpression ->
                    val functionLiteral = this.treeParent
                    val offsetInCall = functionLiteral.startOffset - callExpression.startOffset
                    if (offsetInCall > 0 && callExpression.text.substring(0, offsetInCall).contains('\n')) {
                        return@let indentConfig.indent.repeat(2)
                    }

                    val textBeforeFirstParameter =
                        callExpression.findChildByType(REFERENCE_EXPRESSION)?.text +
                            " { "
                    " ".repeat(textBeforeFirstParameter.length)
                }
// ...
```

